<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>November 26,  2013</strong><p><i>Orange County Register</i><p><strong>Competition aims to foster tomorrow's coders</strong><p><strong>By: Jordan Graham</strong><br><p>


<DIV ID='images_column' STYLE='float: right; width: 35%; margin-left: 1em; '>

<STYLE>
   #images_column IMG  { width: 100%; }
</STYLE>

<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-1.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-2.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-3.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-4.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-5.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-6.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-7.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-8.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-9.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-10.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-11.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-12.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-13.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-14.jpg">
<IMG SRC="/bin/img/photos/news/articles/OCReg-AppJamPlus-Nov2013-15.jpg">

</DIV>



<p>
Outsmart malevolent teachers, escape from school and learn basic science and math.

<p>
That's not the daydream of a cerebral teen, but the action-packed plot of an educational smartphone game designed by four Tarbut V'Torah students as part of an Orange County mobile application design competition.

<p>
The game won third place in last week's AppJam + competition, a 10-week afterschool program created and run by UC Irvine to teach computer programming fundamentals to Orange County middle school students.<!--googleoff: all-->

<p>
In the near future, elementary and middle school computer coding classes could be as commonplace as cursive lessons were for past generations. Many public school districts don't offer any computer programming classes, and in those that do, it often is not taught before high school.

<p>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Department of Commerce has reported a shortage in the number of college students majoring in computer science and has projected a future in which American companies would be forced to look abroad to fill programming positions.

<p>
AppJam+ aims to reverse these trends by giving students their first taste of computer programming at a younger age.

<p>
The middle school competition launched last year as a partnership between UC Irvine's Donald Bren School of Information and Computer Sciences and the OC Stem Initiative (a network of local funders who support science, technology, engineering and math education). This year, 20 teams from five Orange County middle schools competed.

<p>
The directions were simple: Create a smartphone game that could teach science and math to first- through fifth-graders. Teams had to build the applications from scratch, designing background scenery, creating graphics, developing the plot, writing dialogue, picking music and audio effects, and building a program to make it all work.

<p>
Daunting as that may sound, the young competitors learned quickly, thanks to their UCI mentors and App Inventor for Android &ndash; a free online program that makes computer code visual, displaying commands and databases as on-screen puzzle pieces. As students assigned different functions and values to the various sections, they could create a code by snapping the different pieces together.

<p>
&ldquo;It's easier to teach the kids the concepts, but not all the code and everything,&rdquo; said Marc Wong, 22, a program mentor and UCI computer science major. &ldquo;Normally, the code would be numbers, words, all very overwhelming. But if the students learn the foundations of how the code works, they can add the actual coding later.&rdquo;

<p>
On the program's first day, the students created a basic app where a picture of an anteater made a noise when the phone's screen was touched. A few weeks later, they designed a Magic 8 Ball app that provided advice when students shook the phone. During the competition's final class, the students spoke confidently about &ldquo;if-then-else&rdquo; functions &ndash; a common syntax of many computer programming languages &ndash; as they debugged their near-competition-ready mobile applications.

<p>
Sixth-grader Ilan Berdy had no computer programming experience 10 weeks ago, but said he now understood the interactions of computer code and liked the logic behind it.

<p>
&ldquo;It all fits together and it makes sense and you actually understand why everything is happening,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;A few weeks ago, there was that &lsquo;ohhhhh' moment.&rdquo;

<p>
Tarbut V'Torah's five teams created apps that ranged in plot from a horse race where answering math questions correctly boosts the user's speed, to a castaway scenario where the player answers science questions to collect resources for an island escape.

<p>
Though this year's competition has come and gone, the students still have access to the Android app-design program, can continue working on their games, and even have the ability to upload the applications to the Google store when completed.

<p>
Seventh-grader Alex Berry said he signed up for the program because his favorite smartphone game had some flaws he wanted to fix. Now, he's eyeing creating something original.

<p>
&ldquo;Me and my friends always play apps together,&rdquo; Berry said. &ldquo;Now we can make our own.&rdquo;



<div style="float: right; margin: 2em 0;"> 
 &#8212; Photos courtesy of Tarbut V'Torah <br/>
</div>

<br><TITLE>Competition aims to foster tomorrow's coders</TITLE>

